{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"G4 container review (WS2 child vs parent + sibling roster). Findings:\n\n**[G4 / dependency-gap + ordering-violation] WS2 is the producer of the Sonnet-downgrade replacement that WS1's `verifier_cfg` deletion depends on, but no dependency edge encodes this from either side, and it conflicts with the parent's \"WS1 lands FIRST\" prose.**\n- The downgrade-preservation safeguard exists only as prose in WS1's NOTE (\"the deletion of `verifier_cfg` here should land after WS2 so the workflow verify path does not lose the downgrade\"); WS2 (this ticket) has deps=[] and says nothing about being a prerequisite for WS1's deletion. Per the declared graph, WS1 (which the parent says lands FIRST) could ship the `verifier_cfg` deletion before WS2 pins the per-step `model:` Sonnet downgrade → the workflow verify path silently reverts to the runner default (Opus), losing the decisive non-frontier downgrade the epic explicitly wants preserved (parent Success Criteria: \"applies the Sonnet-by-default verifier model\").\n- This is the same hazard already filed on WS1 (80c3), viewed from WS2's side: WS2 produces the declarative replacement; nothing makes WS1's deletion wait for it. Suggested fix: encode the ordering as an enforceable edge (gate WS1's `verifier_cfg`-deletion step on WS2 landing) rather than leaving it as cross-ticket prose, OR reconcile the parent sequencing to state the precise order (WS1 migration + `_run_passes`/`pass2_verify` deletion first, `verifier_cfg` deletion gated on WS2's per-step model pin).\n- criteria: parent Success \"workflow verify step applies the Sonnet-by-default verifier model\"; parent AC WS2 \"pins the decisive non-frontier verifier model (Sonnet) by default\"; WS1 AC \"Once parity passes, ... `verifier_cfg` are deleted\".\n- checklist_item: dependency gap; ordering violation\n- suggested_fix: add an explicit edge so WS1's verifier_cfg deletion is gated on WS2's verify-step model pin (or split that deletion out), and align the parent's \"WS1 first\" prose with this precise ordering.\n\n**[G4 / scope-overlap on plan-review.yaml — verify step] benign co-edit, dep-encoded one direction only; flagged for awareness.**\n- WS2 edits the verify step in `plan-review.yaml` to pin `model: Sonnet`; WS1 edits the same file (probe-mode / criteria subset) and also touches the verify path's return shape / model semantics; WS3 sizes against the verify step's resolved `model:` WS2 pins. WS3→WS2 dep edge exists (consistent). WS1↔WS2 both touch the verify step (WS1 removes `verifier_cfg`'s downgrade, WS2 reintroduces it declaratively on the same step) — the regions interact (the very downgrade WS1 drops is what WS2 restores), which is the substance of the ordering finding above, not a separate merge-conflict-only overlap.\n- impact: Low as a pure file overlap; the material risk is the ordering one above.\n- checklist_item: scope overlap; consumer impact\n- suggested_fix: none beyond the ordering fix above.\n\nNo other modes detected: WS2 docs/editor/BPMN work (`bpmn.py`, `editor.py`, docs) is disjoint from sibling touch-sets (no shared-state, no conflicting assumption, no residual reference). Parent WS2 acceptance criteria (pin+override, properties-panel edit, BPMN round-trip, legacy back-compat, docs) are each carried by this child 1:1 — no coverage gap."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782582340031674001,"uuid":"f55b0766-82e0-45e9-8918-6418f8493942"}